This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a new framework for imitation learning. It also involves the use of state-of-the-art methods such as GAIL and behavior cloning, which are commonly used in machine learning. Additionally, the paper discusses empirical results, which is a common practice in machine learning research. 

The paper may also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as imitation learning is a subfield of AI. 

Furthermore, the paper may be relevant to the sub-category of cs.RO (Robotics) as imitation learning is commonly used in robotics to teach robots how to perform tasks. 

The paper may also be relevant to cs.CV (Computer Vision) as imitation learning can be used in computer vision tasks such as object recognition and tracking. 

Finally, the paper may be relevant to cs.SY (Systems and Control) as imitation learning can be used in control systems to teach robots or agents how to perform tasks.
